            <h3 class="united-states__title mb-15">Student Visa</h3>
            <ul class="checkmark-list">
              <li>
                To study in South Korea, the visa requirements and eligibility criteria vary depending on the university you choose. For Nepalese students, there are two main types of study visas: the
                D-2 Visa and the D-4 Visa.
              </li>
              <li>
                You cannot study your major course at a university or work in South Korea with a D-4 visa. To be eligible to study at a university and work in South Korea, Nepalese students must
                obtain a D-2 visa. To obtain the D-2 visa, it is mandatory to have completed IELTS in Nepal.
              </li>
              <li>Although you can convert your D-4 visa to a D-2 visa after completing a Korean language course in South Korea, doing so is more costly than obtaining a direct D-2 visa.</li>
              <li>
                The D-2 visa grant notice is only valid for 90 days after it is issued to you. This means that you need to arrive in Korea within 90 days of the date on your D-2 visa grant notice.
              </li>
              <li>International students must apply for the Residence Card within 90 days of their arrival in Korea.</li>
              <li>
                The Student Services Team will assist the new students with the application process at the International Student Orientation during New Student Welcome Week. Please note that it
                usually takes approximately 8 weeks to receive the RC. Without RC, you cannot open a bank account.
              </li>
            </ul>
